Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin, Ciaran, Cormac.","English and Irish: variant of   Stanton  . This English name has been established (in this spelling) since medieval times in Ireland (Mayo, Connacht), where it has been Gaelicized as <b>de Stonndún</b>. Compare   McEvilly  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McEvilly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamonn.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Mhílidh</b> ‘son of the knight’, from Gaelic <i>míleadh</i> ‘warrior, knight’. In County Mayo and County Cork, a family of English origin Gaelicized their name from   Staunton   to <i>Mac an Mhílidh</i>, apparently because of the latter's presumed similarity to the name of their ancestor, <i>Milo</i> de Stanton."]},{"name":"Stanton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places in England called Stanton or Staunton, especially Stanton in Staffordshire and Staunton in Worcestershire, all named with Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Most of the placenames come from their situation on stony ground, but in the case of Stanton Harcourt in Oxfordshire and Stanton Drew in Avon the reference is to the proximity of prehistoric stone monuments. The name has also sometimes been chosen by Ashkenazic Jews as an Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames. This surname has also long been established in Ireland (especially Mayo)."]}]},{"name":"Cecily","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecilie","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."]},{"name":"Cicely","meanings":["Variant of   Cecily .  This was a common form of the name in the Middle Ages, and in the 20th century was well known as the name of the British actress and singer  Cicely Courtneidge  (  1893–1980 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":17,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":42,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":55,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":64,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Cecily de Staunton was born in 1273, in Holbrook, Suffolk, England, her father, Earl Richard Fitzalan, was 11270 and her mother, Mrs Earl Richard Fitzalan, was 13. She had at least 2 sons with Henry de Clayton. She died in 1337, in Horsham, Sussex, England, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1273–1337":"1273–1337","1260–1292":"1260–1292","1269–Male":"1269–Surnud","1300–1349":"1300–1349","1290–1332":"1290–1332","1293–Male":"1293–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","about 1293":"umbes 1293","about 1292":"umbes 1292","before 1332":"enne 1332","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1273":"1273","1293":"1293","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1